## Key Concepts

### Gateway Groups

A Gateway Group bundles multiple WAN gateways under a single logical group with assigned tier values. OPNsense routes traffic through the lowest available tier. If a Tier 1 gateway fails monitoring, traffic automatically shifts to Tier 2.

| Tier | Gateway | Behavior |
|------|---------|----------|
| Tier 1 | WAN_DHCP — 10.0.2.1 | Primary — used when online |
| Tier 2 | WAN2_DHCP — 10.0.3.1 | Failover — used when WAN1 fails |

### Gateway Monitoring

OPNsense monitors each gateway by sending ICMP probes to the assigned monitor IP. Gateway states:

| Color | Meaning |
|-------|---------|
| 🟢 Green | Online — gateway reachable |
| 🟡 Yellow | Degraded — packet loss or high latency |
| 🔴 Red | Offline — gateway unreachable |

### Policy-Based Routing

Standard routing uses the system routing table. Policy-based routing uses LAN firewall rules to force specific traffic through a designated gateway group, overriding the default routing table on a per-rule basis.

## Configuration Summary

- Added WAN2 as a second OPNsense interface on Adapter 3 connected to NAT Network 2
- Assigned gateways: WAN → 10.0.2.1, WAN2 → 10.0.3.1
- Configured monitor IPs: WAN → 8.8.4.4, WAN2 → 8.8.8.8
- Created Gateway Group (GW_Group) with WAN at Tier 1 and WAN2 at Tier 2
- Added LAN firewall policy-routing rules directing LAN traffic through GW_Group
- Added DNS routing rule for local DNS resolution
- Configured Outbound NAT for both WAN and WAN2 interfaces
- Disabled direct NAT adapter on Kali Linux to force traffic through OPNsense

## Firewall Rules — LAN (Correct Order)

| Order | Protocol | Source | Destination | Port | Gateway | Purpose |
|-------|----------|--------|-------------|------|---------|---------|
| 1 | IPv4 TCP/UDP | LAN net | 10.200.200.254 | 53 | default | Local DNS resolution |
| 2 | IPv4 any | LAN net | any | any | GW_Group | Policy route through failover group |
| 3 | IPv6 any | LAN net | any | any | default | Default IPv6 allow |

> The DNS rule must always appear before the Gateway Group rule. Without it, DNS queries are routed through GW_Group and may fail during failover transitions.

