## Issues Encountered and Resolved

### Issue 1 — Kali Traffic Bypassing OPNsense

**Symptom:** Traceroute showed a single hop directly to Google DNS without traversing OPNsense. Policy routing had no effect.

**Root Cause:** Kali Linux had an active VirtualBox NAT adapter alongside the OPNsense LAN adapter. Windows used the lower-metric NAT adapter for all internet traffic, bypassing OPNsense and the Gateway Group entirely.

**Resolution:** Disabled the VirtualBox NAT adapter on Kali and forced all traffic through OPNsense LAN gateway at 10.200.200.254.

**Validation:** Traceroute after fix:
```
1  10.200.200.254   ← OPNsense LAN gateway ✓
2  10.0.2.1         ← WAN1 upstream ✓
3  ...further hops
```

> This is a recurring lab rule: all client VMs must have their VirtualBox NAT adapters disabled. Any active secondary NAT adapter bypasses all OPNsense controls.

---

### Issue 2 — WAN2 Gateway Bound to Wrong Interface

**Symptom:** After disabling WAN1 to simulate failure, both WAN1 and WAN2 appeared offline instead of WAN2 taking over.

**Root Cause:** The WAN2 gateway was incorrectly assigned to the WAN interface instead of the WAN2 interface. Both gateways were pointing at em0, so disabling WAN1 killed both paths simultaneously.

**Resolution:** Corrected the interface binding for WAN2_DHCP gateway to point to the WAN2 interface (em2).

---

### Issue 3 — pfSync from EP5 HA Configuration Hijacking em2 (Root Cause of All WAN2 Issues)

**Symptom:** WAN2 stuck at yellow/degraded state with 100% packet loss. ifconfig showed em2 with IP `10.0.0.2` instead of an address from NAT Network 2 (10.0.3.x). dhclient on em2 never received a lease from NAT Network 2.

**Root Cause:** The High Availability configuration from EP5 left pfSync actively running on em2 with a hardcoded static IP of `10.0.0.2` (the old backup sync IP). When WAN2 was assigned to em2, pfSync owned the interface first and its static IP took precedence over DHCP from NAT Network 2. OPNsense gateway monitoring was trying to reach 8.8.8.8 through the 10.0.0.0/24 sync network — which had no internet path — causing permanent 100% packet loss.

**ifconfig evidence:**
```
em2: description: WAN2 (opt1)
     inet 10.0.0.2 netmask 0xffffff00    ← old pfSync IP, wrong network
     syncdev: em2 syncpeer: 10.0.0.1     ← pfSync still active
     groups: pfsync                       ← em2 still a sync interface
```

**Resolution:**

Step 1 — Disabled pfSync in OPNsense GUI:
```
System → High Availability → Settings
→ Uncheck "Synchronize States (pfsync)"
→ Clear Synchronize Peer IP
→ Save
```

Step 2 — Removed old static IP and renewed DHCP:
```bash
ifconfig em2 delete 10.0.0.2
dhclient em2
```

Step 3 — DHCP result:
```
DHCPOFFER from 10.0.3.3
Bound to 10.0.3.6    ← correct IP from NAT Network 2 ✓
```

Step 4 — Renewed WAN1 after reconnecting Adapter 1:
```bash
dhclient em0
```

Step 5 — Verified all IPs:
```bash
ifconfig -a | grep "inet "
```
```
inet 10.200.200.254    ← LAN ✓
inet 10.0.3.6          ← WAN2 correct ✓
inet 127.0.0.1
```

> **Key lesson:** Always clean up previous episode configurations before starting a new lab setup. Leftover pfSync configuration from an HA deployment will silently conflict with any new interface assignment on the same adapter.

